This paper is about generative adversarial networks (GANs), which are widely used in machine learning and artificial intelligence. The paper specifically focuses on Wasserstein GANs (WGANs), which are a successful variant of GANs. The paper discusses the convergence of stochastic gradient descent-ascent when the generator is a one-layer network. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.SY (Systems and Control).
